                    "text": "8,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 108,
                    "end": 110,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "9]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Presented results include the statistical uncertainty and a first estimate of systematic uncertainty (still under studies are detector effects and influence of feed-down).",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The multiplicity fluctuations were addressed using the scaled variance measure, \u03c9 i of the multiplicity distribution. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "It is defined as \u03c9 =",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": ", where N i and N 2 i are the mean multiplicity and the second moment of the multiplicity distribution of particles of type i, respectively. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The scaled variance is an intensive measure [10], i.e. it is independent of the number of wounded nucleons in the Wounded Nucleon Model [11] or volume in the Grand Canonical Ensemble, but it depends on their fluctuations. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 44,
                    "end": 48,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[10]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 136,
                    "end": 140,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[11]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The latter feature makes it difficult to compare results from p+p interactions with those from nucleus+nucleus collisions. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "For the Poisson distribution \u03c9 = 1. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 2 (left) shows the scaled variance of \u03c0, K and p +p. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Figure 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The scaled variance of all considered particle types increases with increasing energy. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Rich data on the charged particle multiplicity distribution in the full phase space obey the KNO scaling [12,13]. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
