                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "13]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "From this scaling follows a linear increase of the scaled variance with the mean multiplicity of charged particles visible as an increase of \u03c9 \u03c0 with collision energy (see the bottom left panel of Fig. 2). ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 197,
                    "end": 203,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The scaled variance of unidentified charged hadrons measured within the acceptance chosen for this analysis is shown in the same panel by purple diamonds. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The increase with collision energy is weaker than that measured in the full phase space, but agreement between \u03c9 N ch and \u03c9 \u03c0 as well as between N and N \u03c0 indicates that KNO scaling may also apply to pion production. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Figure 2 (right) shows the energy dependence of \u03c9 p , \u03c9 K + , and \u03c9 \u03c0 + . ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Figure 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The scaled variance of identified positively charged hadrons is smaller than the one measured for the sum of charges. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Moreover, in the case of positively charged hadrons, instead of an increase with the collision energy the scaled variance is approximately independent of energy. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The suppressed (<1) values of \u03c9 p+p and \u03c9 p are probably due to the baryon number conservation [14]. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 95,
                    "end": 99,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[14]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In p+p interactions, the net baryon number is two, thus, fluctuations of the sum of charges is dominated by protons [14]. ",
            "section": "NA61/SHINE identified hadron fluctuation studies",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
